@section Manage words

Managing words is about definitions, singulars, plurals, synonims and
antonims

We can start building singulars and plurals from a word. You can read
the test file:

@example
import unittest
import nltk
from nltk.stem import *
from nltk.stem.snowball import SnowballStemmer

class TddInPythonExample(unittest.TestCase):

    def test_stem_returns_correct_result(self):
        stemmer = PorterStemmer()
        self.assertEqual(stemmer.stem("vuelos"), "vuelo")

    def test_snowball_stem_returns_correct_result(self):
        sb = SnowballStemmer("english").stem("generously")
        self.assertEqual(sb, "generous")
@end example

You can test it with:

@example
$ nosetest3 test/test_stem.py
@end example

Another tool for NLP tasks is to retrieve synonims and antonims from
words. You can execute the tests:

@example
$ nosetest3 test/test_syn.py
@end example

Another way is using wordnet:

@example
$ nosetests3 test/test_wordnet.py
@end example

Wordnet provides measures about semantic similarity between
words, definitions about words, ...

